bug.short_desc: Add/Remove Modules dialog missing module children

long_desc.thetext:
The Add/Remove modules dialog only displays a module and its direct child modules. Sometime since 0.7 (this is a regression) it stopped displaying child modules of the children.
As an example, consider a server that supports the full J2EE project structure in WTP - EARs that contain J2EE modules (incl. Web) and utility jars, where Web modules can also contain utility jars. When you go to add the EAR to the server, the Add/Remove Modules dialog would only show the EAR and its direct children, e.g.:
MyEAR MyWeb MyEJB
Once you've added it to the server, the Servers view correctly shows the utility jar within the Web module:
MyEAR MyWeb MyUtility MyEJB
Since this is a regression and may confuse people enough that they don't go ahead and add the project to the server to see that it does actually work, I'm marking it as major.

Created an attachment (id=51026) Patch to show child modules
The patch adds support for displaying child modules.
Sending for PMC approval in 1.5.2.

+1 Except I really do not like to see + } catch (Exception e) { + // ignore + } in code. Can you explain its safe to ignore _any_ exception that's thrown here? (And, perhaps add to the comment, instead of just 'ignore').
I'd approve this as well if the exception catch was refined further.

+1 Maybe our module API should be reviewed for cases where excpetion thrown are not very useful.
I think a good example is eclipse resource API where exceptions usually indicate cases where it is crucial to take an compensating action.

The try/catch block came from an identical code block that I copied from directly above this in the method. The getChildModules() method was originally spec'd to throw an exception. The exception was removed since this code was written and it looks like even a rouge server adopter couldn't cause harm, but this code was missed in the clean up.
Since I'm duplicating code that's already there and I know it doesn't cause problems, I'm going to release it now and fix both in the 2.0 stream.
Fix released to 1.5.2 and 2.0 streams.
+1 for WTP 1.5.2

bug.short_desc: Relax restriction on StandardVMRunner

long_desc.thetext:
Thread on newsgroup eclipse.newcomer:
>If a class is marked as "Discouraged Access", how discouraged should we be >from extending and using it? > Discouraged means you should neither extend nor use it. In Eclipse for example all internal types are marked discouraged. If you use one of these you must accept being broken with the next build since it can totally change or completely disappear.
> Specifically, is it safe to extend a class like >StandardVMRunner, > No.
>or should we extend the abstract class (and duplicate a >lot of StandardVMRunner's code in the process)? > > Do this and file an enhancement request to make the StandardVMRunner API.
Dani
Is it possible to not discourage access to StandardVMRunner so we don't have duplicate all of its code in our own class? All we needed to do was override the run method, but since the class is internal, we had to extend AbstractVMRunner and copy most of the content of StandardVMRunner into our class.
Moving to Debug.
We don't have plans to make the standard VM runner/debugger API in 3.3

bug.short_desc: Mylar doesn't allow to edit defined task queries

long_desc.thetext: Once task query has been defined, it can't be modified. Suggestion: add "Properties" to query context window and/or add Ctrl-Enter support for opening "Query Properties" dialog similiar to new query dialog.

You can double-click on query task or just <enter>, but yes, this is not intuitive since there is no UI saying this is possible.
I remember when I didn't know how to edit and I had to delete and create a new query every time.
After some time monkey-clicking I discovered this, but forgot to open a bug :)

Good suggestions. Done, so this is now consistent with the way projects and Task Repositories behave.. The problem with removing "Open" alltoghter is that it put "Open with Browser" as the top item for a query, which is too weird. So I'm leaving both in for now but we need to refine this for 1.0. Still need to add Alt+Enter shortcut, but that will be done with bug 145884.
Resolved.
Created an attachment (id=51101) mylar/context/zip
Marking fixed (for real this time).
Mik, in the latest dev-build there is a action called "Properties" with Ctrl+Enter bound, but it doesn't work (the keybinding). Just <Enter> works fine.

Yes, I didn't commit removing that binding until after the build. But thanks for the reminder.
Btw, the weird thing right now is that we have both Open and Properties that do the same thing. It was just too strange removing "Open" because then the first thing in the menu was "Open with Browser". We'll have to fix this up for 0.8.0.

In the other side, the properties thing sounds strange too.
If you are a Eclipse developer it is natural to expect it to open a standard Properties dialog.
I don't remember any properties command whose behavior is different from this.
"Open" sounds like you are getting the query results.
I think "Edit" sounds good in this specific case. There can be a "Edit" command before "Open in Browser" bound to Enter keybinding.
What do you think?
Open is weird. I'd go for edit or properties- whichever is more platform-confirming.

I like "Edit", but the workbench typically uses "Open" for "Edit", and we almost always try to err on the side of being platform-conforming. Agreed that "Open" is weird, and the expectation should be that you get an editor when you click that. Also, we're likely to create a New menu with sub-menus that will be the top item, so the point I make about "Open with Browser" being on top should be irrelevant for 1.0. So I'm leaning towards keeping Properties and eventually getting rid of "Open", since as this report indicates some will be expecting it in "Properties". If anyone think of a similar example in the SDK or another tool please post it.

bug.short_desc: [hotbug][j2ee] 'EAR Libraries' does not include JAR files in directories

long_desc.thetext:
JAR files included in any directory under 'EARContent' are not included in the 'EAR Libraries' classpath container.
I have imported an EAR file that contains an EJB JAR file as well as a JAR file (log4j) that resides the 'lib' directory which the EJB JAR depends on. The MANIFEST.MF for the EJB JAR contains the following:
Manifest-Version: 1.0 Class-Path: lib/log4j.jar
The log4j.jar file is copied correctly to the EARContent\lib directory upon importing but the EJB project that is constructed does not contain log4j on the classpath (nor in the 'EAR Libraries' container). Upon further investigation I found that it was because the JAR file is not in the 'EARContent' directory, but rather it is in a sub-directory of the EARContent directory. If I move the log4j.jar from the 'EARContent\lib' directory to the 'EARContent' directory, fix up the MANIFEST.MF file (manually, due to bug 159017) then the log4j.jar is added to the 'EAR Libraries' container and therefore is on the classpath of my EJB project.

I am flagging this as a hot-bug as it is a regression from the WTP 1.0.x release where this did work - just in a different manner (i.e. the 'EAR Libraries' didn't exist) - and is therefore a regression in our product that adopts WTP. This is a problem for our headless tooling which relies upon EAR import to setup the classpath correctly for ejb modules.
In WTP 1.0.x dependant JAR files in the MANIFEST.MF file of an EJB-JAR were automatically included in the classpath of the EJB Project during EAR import (no matter where they were located - as long as they reside in the EAR project). bug.short_desc: No feedback the state of the state

long_desc.thetext:
users of PDE are inherently manipulating a set of plugins in a State. That state is resolved and various bundles are wired together. From time to time the wirings go wrong or are unexpected. When this happens it would be good for users to inspect the state and follow the wires and diagnose the problems. This is very much like the functions provide in the OSGi console (e.g., ss, diag, package, ..) but on the PDE state not the framework's state.
The Equinox team would be delighted to supply any underlying infrastructure needed in addition to the state helper etc and humbly request that the PDE UI wizards expose this somehow in the UI.
I would almost want to tie this into the bundle management plan item we have. It would be nice to have a UI "console" that you can inspect an environment.

This is certainly a very useful function.
I believe PDE already has all the information on what is wrong with the state. The challenge is in the UI rendering of the state. That is, what you want is really a real-time version of the 'validate plug-in set' that we have on the Plug-ins tab of the PDE launchers.
However, if you observe how we report the errors there, it is easy to see that a tree viewer can only do so much. It is very hard to clearly render a chain reaction with a tree viewer.
We were planning on doing alternative explorations to visualize dependency graphs and states, but the effort is currently blocked (bug 155494).

Note also that our coop student Richard Keelan has adapted the regular framework console commands that look at the state to work on the PDE state. This surfaces as a "PDE Console". I believe he has something to show for this now. Perhaps he can attach the code here or link to another bug that has the code.

i tried that, but there are a lot of problems working that way. one example: one of my rcp-projects needs the nls-plugins (cause the applications language should be in german), after i "installed" the nls-plugins the automatic build system of my other rcp-projects (which don't need the nls-plugins) crashes cause the languages changing to german, i must change all the other rcp-projects run configurations that they start in english...
Interestingly, moments ago I was talking with Kai Todter and quite spontaineously he pointed out the same need.

The performance of trying to keep track of multiple target is not practical. I have been called crazy many times by Wassim for implying such an idea. Resolver states are far from light weight and do not scale well.
As a work around for such a problem (though it does not seem like it will work for this one) would be to create one big state that is a super set of all the states. Then some how define a subset of which you wish to develop against. If you then reference any plugins outside of your subset, you would receive a warning/error of some kind. This would represent mini target runtimes, allowing the user to develop against more than one mini target at a time.
Since Wassim should be coming back soon, I will let him do what he sees fit for this bug. I know if I agreed to this bug, he would come down here and kill me :)

as Brian points out, having a target platform per plugin project is not as simple as having a separate JRE per project. It is both impractical and confusing.
While a project's relationship with a JRE is local (politics), a target platform is an envrionment and a state (ie. federal politics).
Target platforms can be thousands of plug-ins large. Each target platform comes with a huge memory footprint: a state, models, extension registries, etc.
Also, workspaces may contain thousands of projects. Each with its own distinct target? the costs become astronomical.
Performance-aside: I have a plug-in project in my workspace that contributes a view. Sometimes i want to run it against the entire SDK. Other times, I want to run it as a standalone RCP application. Why would I want to tie this plug-in to a particular target?
Intra-workspace relations: Also, how would the workspace plug-ins relate to each other? Do they belong to the same state and reference each other?
i. If yes, then effectively all separate target platforms/states will now effectively be merged and we are back where we were.
ii. if no, then the workspace has become a confusing place.
I would like to see a proposal from people who need this function that attempt to address these issues.

bug.short_desc: Deadlock caused by FontNameContributionItem

long_desc.thetext:
We are running a Job in a worker thread that executes commands in the DiagramEditingDomain. As it uses a transaction, the EditingDomin is locked. In the pre-execute phase of the command, an OperationHistoryEvent is fired. The FontNameContributionItem is registered as a listener for these events. In AbstractContributionItem.historyNotification() it tries to execute an update synchronoously on the display thread. So this thread locks the editing domain and tries to access the display thread.
At the same time, the UISynchronizer tries to refresh the FontNameContributionItem in the display thread. That one tries to read the font name property using an runExclusive() command in PropertyChangeContributionItem.getPropertyValue(). As the EditingDomain is locked by the worker and the UISynchronizer blocks the display thread, a deadlock occurs.
Removing the runExclusive() solves the problem. We have found other places where runExclusive() calls have been commented out, too.
The attached patch fixes the problem.
We are currently developing a product that heavily relies on GMF. As we want to use the framework as is, it would help us a lot if this path made it into 1.0.1.
Regards Jan
Created an attachment (id=51075) Fixes deadlock caused by FontNameContributionItem

But that's the point. We must not do any refactoring because the miner ID is part of the dstore protocol and thus part of external API. If we were to refactor this, TM 2.x would no longer work against TM 2.0 servers, would it?

If we were to > refactor this, TM 2.x would no longer work against TM 2.0 servers, would it? >
The miner ID isn't part of the dstore protocol, itself, it's really just the protocol for that particular miner. Are saying you don't want to be constrained by having the ID public - and would prefer that it were not external API? I'm presuming you want to have the option of refactoring the miner in TM 2.x (in the client code-based) - but the miner is already public API and therefore cannot be refactored in 2.x, can it?

I think that essentially, the miner ID is already API because if we went and refactored the miner into a different package for 3.0, then a 2.x client would not work against a 3.0 server (unless we provided a compatibility package).
So what I'm saying is: - the miner ID is already API and cannot be changed/refactored without notice - therefore it should also be made explicit - therefore I'd recommend having it in a String constant rather than implicit through MinerClass.getClass().getName().

bug.short_desc: [API] Supports definition of a dataSource extension's relationship

long_desc.thetext: For ease of extensibility, adds support for an oda.dataSource runtime extension to specifiy its relationship.

Added an optional element in the oda.dataSource extension point schema to define the relationship of a data source extension. The initial type of relationship, supported in 1.0 M2, is to specify that an extension is deprecated and its replacing oda data source id. Added related methods in the oda.util.manifest.ExtensionManifest to access the content of the relationship element. It is up to an ODA host to apply the relationship definition as appropriate, e.g. to migrate its reference of a deprecated extension, and to control which ODA extension to use at runtime.

In 1.0 M3, added an optional sub-element to the dataSet element in the oda.dataSource extension point schema to define a data set relationship. Added related methods in the oda.util.manifest.DataSetType to access the content of the associated relationship element. The relationship of a data source is now directly associated with the dataSource element.
Completed the scope intended for 1.0 release.
Verified and closed.

bug.short_desc: [Viewers] Need a Go Into that conserves the TreePath

long_desc.thetext:
Currently, Go Into is usually implemented by storing the state of the viewer in a TreeFrame and setting the selected element as new input. This means that all subsequently created TreePaths will not contain the path to the selected element, thus breaking any path based logic in the content/label providers and other receivers.
I would expect to always receive the same TreePath, regardless of being in a Go Into mode or not.
Not sure if this is an issue with viewers themselves or with the Go Into support (whose ownership is questionable)

I would like to wait on this one and see if it can be solved differently (i.e. without changing TreeViewer).
One possible solution for this is a new method TreeViewer.setPrefix(TreePath treePath), with the tree viewer adding this prefix to all paths when it calls the content provider/label provider, fires a selection change etc, and removing this prefix from all paths when it is being called (add/remove/refresh/update).
